data.text:
Facts I thought were important for the project:
- Lifespan of Females is one to two weeks in nature, up to 42 - 56 days in a controlled environment.  Males ~ 10 days.
- Most mosquito's stay within a mile or two of their source.
- Egg, Larva, Pupa are the three stages of development and these stages last 5 to 14 days.
- Freezing water does not kill them!  They go into "diaapause" which is a delay in their development until favorable temperatures and climate occur.
- Mosquito's find their prey by chemical, visual, and heat sensors.
- Feeding preferences of mosquito's are Type O blood types, heavy breathers, those with a lot of skin bacteria, people with a lot of body heat and pregnancy.
- They feed at Dusk and Dawn.
- Females are the vectors for many diseases.

Mosquito Control
- Predators are certain species of fish, dragonflies, some species of lizard and geckos.
- Another method is to introduce a large number of sterile males
- Ulta sounds will keep mosquito's away.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mosquito

listing.overview: Connect Bitbucket and Trello to help your software team plan and track work.
listing.description:
The Bitbucket Cloud Power-up allows your team to attach branches, commits and pull requests to cards, and populates with real-time status updates. When you are ready to move from Trello to Bitbucket create a branch directly from a card. Seamlessly move from Trello to Bitbucket while maintaining traceability.

The Bitbucket Cloud Power-up allows you to:

- Quickly jump to Bitbucket by creating a link on your board.
- Attach branches, commits and pull requests to cards.
- See important information regarding your code from the card.
- Show the status of your pull requests and other linked information from the front of the card.

data.text:
**Presentation**
* Audience: You are presenting to members of the CDC. Some members of the audience will be biostatisticians and epidemiologists who will understand your models and metrics and will want more information. Others will be decision-makers, focusing almost exclusively on your cost-benefit analysis. Your job is to convince both groups of the best course of action in the same meeting and be able to answer questions that either group may ask.
* The length of your presentation should be about 20 minutes (a rough guideline: 2 minute intro, 10 minutes on model, 5 minutes on cost-benefit analysis, 3 minute recommendations/conclusion).  Touch base with your local instructor... er, manager... for specific logistic requirements!
Remember to write notes when something is completed.
